note.p: This word is formed out of a "g" with a suspension stroke and a lenition mark; it is not clear what form could be understood here that would require a lenited consonant other than "gho", perhaps modelled on prep. dha.

w.lemmaSL: ioruaidh mac dreguinn mhic duil rí fer cefpta

note.p: Ronald Black (0080846) has erroneously noted Foirne as the brother of rí an Innia rather than the brother of rí Lochlann.
Black (0131203) has taken this as urra, however the context favours the interpretation of a form of farrad.

Black took sgiobhidh to be a form of sgioba, 'crew' (0120461), and tentatively took asguind as éasgaidh, 'nimble' (0021043). However, as this section describes the readying of the ships to set sail, and as the following phrase uses the same syntax to describe the preparation involved, this phrase appears to be best understood as consisting of the verbal noun sgiabadh, 'moving', the possessive a, and the genitive of the noun sgonn, '[block(s) of] wood'.
Black made a very tentative translation of sirrginn as 'jerkin' (0120674), however seirrcenn, a type of boat, better fits the context.

Black (0061174) has noted the possibility that dis in this context may mean prow. As a ship narrows towards its prow, dis has been understood as a form of tís in this transcription, with the form tíslethan consequently being understood as wide-hulled.

Black (0060409) understood this to be cruinneach, with the meaning given as 'ball-rounded'. It does, however, seem that a form of crithnaigthech, with the compound meaning 'making the ropes/rigging shake’ may be more appropriate given the power implied by the other preceding adjectives.
Black opined that if troitheadh 'is not error for srothadh, it is some word for the rough surface of the sea' (0130860).
Black (0100540) took this to be a form of lìonadh.
Black suggested that this may be composed of possessive a and the genitive of ball (0030090). The syntax of the sentence would not support such a reading, however.
Black has understood this compound somewhat differently, taking it as 'full-winded' (0090039).
Black posited that ropin may mean 'sheets' (0070665), although in this context a word for rope would make more sense.

Black (0020534) postulated that this compound may mean 'tricky-to-hoist'. The placement of a question mark after this interpretation, however, would appear to indicate that he was somewhat doubtful of this interpretation.
Ronald Black interpreted the word as being from Boillsgeanta (0080846), and meaning 'shining'. Thr form, however, is closer to basganta.
Black (0002839) as a single word and as the dative plural of súgad.
Black understands this as taisdealach (0121124). An adjective derived from tustall, with a meaning of 'rushing' or 'quick-moving' would be more appropriate here.
Black (0120466) took this to be a form of cladh, with epenthetic vowel, and sgìth.
Black took this to be a form of druim to mean 'wave' (0070695). A version of drumman, usually meaning 'hillock' and by transfer 'wave', seems more likely however.

Black took this to mean do-fhreagartha (0070402), translated as 'unanswerable, matchless'. If fresgirra is understood as a form ofdo-thrascartha, meaning something akin to 'unconquerable', this may be a more suitable descriptor of the sea.

Black provides the same reading as this transcription but did not provide a translation (0081048). The HDSG notes on the same word say that 'The exact reading of this word is uncertain [and] the meaning of it evades me' (0081048).
The brecht component could be from brecht, as above, or brecc as in Black's notes (0030741).

p.note: Black has interpreted gabh as part of a compound gabh thar, meaning 'to put on, assume' (0081088). In this passage, however, we get do ghabh a muir [..] a brat lethann [...] fairis, indicating that the sea covered the party, presumably meaning that a wave washed over the fleet.

note.p: Black took this to be a form of eagconnla (0070860).

O'Rahilly (1962): l.55, has caithem in this position Black (0031067) understood caichadh to be a form of caithem based on O'Rahilly's edition. If caichadh is understood as a form of cathadh, however, it would appear to mean that their words were lost to the wind because of the strength of it.

Black (0002847) understood this as a form of suidhe. A form of sùdh, meaning the overlap of the planks in a clincher-built boat may be more appropriate given the destruction implied by the planks coming apart.
Black took this to be a form of troladh, meaning 'damage' (0130859).

Both Black (0020109) and O'Rahilly (1962): l.63, have taken this as a form of adbar, meaning 'timber'. Another possibility is that it comes from ábur, meaning 'oar-hole'. As the latter is less frequently attested than the word adbar, the former is probably more likley.

Black took this as a from of tarr (0130052) and bruthadh (0002124). As a verbal noun is needed to describe some sort of destruction of the druimdirech mentioned immediately before, tarr would not work as the first element of this word.
Black (0070664) took this compound to mean 'sheet' but a compound word with rop, 'rope' as the second element is more likely.
Black (0081133) understood this as being a form of gàireach, not garg as in this transcription.
Black (0100905) understood this to be màthaireil, not muintremail as in this transcription.
Unlike the present transcription, Black understood this a single word, maolann (0100981).
Black (0110723) thought should have been a form of uisce, rather than as a form of airde as it is understood in the present transcription.

note.p: This is one of AmacMA's quirky agus abreviations. He has more in the next few pages, although they usually look like lightning rods.
The b in this word is badly formed and resembles an l.
Black (0070455) has the headword do-gabhaim listed and in the notes section says 'VN aotin'. Any idea what this word is, WGI? I think it needs to be something like idir or 'earlier'.

Of this form Black (0130915) says that 'This a rather amusing corruption. The original text (cf. O'Rahilly's ed. [(1962)] l. 102) has a ndubhchonn "chants". Alasdair has assimilated this to tùchan "cooing of a dove".'. The MS could, however, be simply representing dúchann, given other instances of other t/d alternations, e.g. p.7, l.27 dusa for (a)tú-sa.
The present transcriber understands this as the Early Gaeliccétóir. Black analysed it as two words, ceud (0040042) and úair (0130991), albeit with the same meaning as cétóir.
I am not confident about how I have analysed this line.

Black (0101006) has màireach as the headword here. Mac Mhaighsdir Alasdair also has the phrase written as three words ar na mhairich. This appears to indicate that the phrase has been re-analysed as a preposition, article, and noun.
Black (0002069) appears not to have known of the prefix abar/amar when writing this slip.
Black took this as a compound formed from lúth (0100696) and bechtach (0030220), unlike this transcription in which it is understood to be a compound from lúb and échtach

note.p: Any further thoughts on this verse appreciated. Not sure how to read the last line. The first three, I think are: The head of Madan Delbchasach son of Duinne/ by me in my hand, o Conn/ thirty warriors who came with the King of G. were laid low/ since he went around them ...
Unlike how it has been understood in this transcription, Black (0120702) took this as a form of slán, saying that he could not account for the spelling.
Black (0020239) takes this as aidhbhseach, meaning 'fearsome', although I am unaware of a headword in Dwelly or the DIL which would suggest such a meaning.
Black (0060957) understood this to be a single word, dealanaich, lightening, unlike this transcription in which it is understood as a compound word consisting of dé and lannach.

Black (0120913) takes this as soiséanach, 'easily-hiding', and HDSG as so-seunach, however the idea of the two spears creating noise, as suggested by the dictionary headwords noted here, would seem to make more sense.

I'm not sure about this HW. If we go for álaig, meaning 'Habit, behaviour, practice', I would think this would have to mean deed(s) here. Other possibilities I have entertained are ar álich(adh), from OIr adlaic (which we would need to take as 'and on necessity in that mutual-smiting by them ...') and eileachadh 'accusation' (which would need to be interpretated as their spear-throwing being a wee skirmish inviting combat before they fight proper), although neither of those seem to really fit with other versions of CF, or with preceding sentence's 'do ionsudur a cheile'. Black (0100497) took the stroke here as an m-stroke, resulting in a reading er am lichadh and suggested a meaning of 'battering, struggling'.

Black (0010284) took the first part of this word as tom, transcribing the piece of text in question as 'do thoumchromidir na toin' and giving a translation of 'backsides bent into the hillocks'. What Black takes as the letter m could be either an m or in when compared with the same in the surrounding text. Based on this, this transcription has understood the first part of this word to be a form of tón, 'bum', with the compound tónchromm understood to be as to squat.
Black (0010112) suggests the headword riodhanach which is not attested in Dwelly or the DIL.
srathrich from srathach (Dwelly) 'Full of straths or valley', srethach (DIL), 'in series, in order' (i.e. straight-arranged noses). Black (0120968) took this as OIr srathach meaning 'saddle-like'.

I know this is inserted above with a careat mark, but it would make more sense not to be there (I think). There are two dots over the two cs but I wonder if those are indicating to delete the word rather than to lenite the cs. Does that make sense to ye?
Black (0080729) understood this to be a form of fód, meaning 'clot', but I have not found a source for this in Dwelly or in DIL.
Black (0030184)takes this as barr. The present transcriber can not see how this would fit into the sentence.
Black (0060849) understood this as a form of darach.

Black (0030726) says that 'O'Rahilly's ed.[1962] has tuc urchur de uimpe for this phrase [and] I suspect this means something similar. Bráth must here be a part of the body, cf. Dwelly brá "brow"? - "He smashed him around it?"'. This transcription understand it to mean something akin to 'destructive blow'.
Black (0010300) took this as a form of the preposition trasna. If we understand brath as a word meaning blow, this then appears to be an adjective.
HW ok?
Do we think this is a fada?
HW ok?

WGI, EPT, regarding this abbreviation that resembles a z (in Times New Roman font), I thought it might be for lao in laoch. In the HDSG slips, however, I have come across Ronnie Black giving a quote including expanding an instance of this abbreviation. There, he expands as allmarach, with the colon afterwards, when it appears, therefore appearing to be the abbreviation for an ending (often probably -ib(h)) due to us being able to see the spread of the dative plural to other plurals in AMD's work here.

This letters appears to be an s with a subsequent horizontal stroke from the descender of the s from left to right, the purpose of which is unclear ot the present transcriber/editor. Despite this extra horizontal stroke, this letter form does not resemble mac Mhaighsdir Alasdair's forms of the letter f. Comparison with O'Rahilly (1962): l.330, wherein the character in question appears as 'Sighmall ua Midir' supports the reading of a name beginning with s and the same charachter further appears as 'siodhmhall' on this folio (p.12, l.19).
This character earlier appeared as 'Néamhinach' (p.12, l.13).

As in l.13 of this folio, this characters appears to be an s with an extra horizontal stroke to the right of the descender, extending from the middle of that letter. The use of such he is puzzling but hte letter from does not resemble the scribe's usual form of f where the top is more rounded. In the forms of s, the upper stroke of the letter tends to be more pointed. Furthermore, in forms of f there is usually more a larger space betwwen the upper stroke and the horizontal stroke from the descender rightwards.
WGI, EPT, I have been debating whether both ag and is are part of the word agus with zero copula, or if we should amend ag to agus as I have done here. Thought on this matter appreciated.
WGI, EPT, do we think it's plausible that this character is 'Finbar of the mead'?

note.p: WGI, EPT, I am not particularly confident about how I've parsed this verse. All feedback.suggestions gratefully received.
Black's note on the form gonin (0090509) appears to understand it as a conjugated form of the verb rather than a noun, as it is understood in the present transcription.
O'Rahilly (1962): p.49 has cenn, not a from of corp here, which would appears to make more sense.
WGI, EPT, I have marked this as the conj. día, but see Black's notes that it 'Seems to be a transitional form' between dá and na. Would it be better marked as from the headword nam.

WGI, EPT: Regarding the headword for claonruidhe, O'Rahilly's edition (1962),: p.50, has Cathair Claonratha, while Ó Siochfhrada's text has Cathair Connraoi. This, I would postulate, is somewhere between the two and looking for a second opinion on ruidhe from rí?

Black (0060286) gives this headword as crith, although the -e ending would suggest it is the variant creathadh.
